-- ── Enigma 1/2 BBS ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$ENiGMA½ is a free, open-source, modern Bulletin Board System (BBS) package written in Node.js that recreates the classic dial-up BBS experience over Telnet, SSH, and WebSocket for today's internet.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Free / Open Source$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2015, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$Independent open-source project (single primary maintainer plus community contributors)$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Not applicable (distributed open-source community project)$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$ENiGMA½ BBS Review 2026: Setup, Features & Doors Guide$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$ENiGMA½ BBS review: a free, open-source, modern Node.js Bulletin Board System with Telnet, SSH, DOS door emulation, and FidoNet support. Setup and features.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$ENiGMA½ (styled ENiGMA 1/2, and referred to on the web as Enigma 1/2 BBS) is a free, open-source Bulletin Board System (BBS) software package, built entirely from scratch in Node.js, that recreates the classic dial-up BBS experience of the 1980s and 1990s for the modern internet. The project was authored by Bryan Ashby, who goes by the online handle NuSkooler, and development began around October 2015; it is distributed on GitHub under the NuSkooler account (github.com/NuSkooler/enigma-bbs) and released under the permissive BSD-2-Clause license, meaning anyone can freely use, modify, and redistribute it, including for commercial purposes, with minimal restriction. A BBS, for readers unfamiliar with the format, is a text-based multi-user online system that predates the modern web, where users dial in (originally over a telephone modem, now over the internet) to read and post public message boards, exchange private messages, download and upload files, play door games, and socialize with other members of that BBS's community; the format largely died out in the mid-to-late 1990s as the World Wide Web became dominant, but has retained a small, dedicated hobbyist following that keeps running new and legacy BBS systems for nostalgia, retrocomputing culture, and old-school community building. ENiGMA½ is one of the most actively developed and feature-rich modern BBS packages available, explicitly designed to be cross-platform: it runs anywhere Node.js runs, with confirmed support on Linux, FreeBSD, OpenBSD, macOS, and Windows, and supports unlimited simultaneous connected users (nodes) limited only by the host machine's resources. Users connect via Telnet, SSH, or secure and non-secure WebSocket, which means ENiGMA½ boards are reachable both from traditional terminal-based BBS client software and from modern browser-based Telnet/SSH gateways like fTelnet. The software is deeply customizable through an HJSON-based (human-friendly JSON) configuration system covering menus, themes, and color schemes, and supports JavaScript-based mods for extending functionality beyond the core. Notably for retrocomputing enthusiasts, ENiGMA½ includes native x86/DOS door game emulation built on the v86 emulator, allowing classic DOS-era BBS door games such as Legend of the Red Dragon (LORD), TradeWars, and Pimpwars to run directly inside the BBS with zero external dependencies, no separate DOSBox, QEMU, or DOSEMU installation required, which is a significant technical achievement that distinguishes ENiGMA½ from most other modern BBS software. Additional standout features include a Z-Machine interpreter that runs classic Infocom interactive fiction titles natively within Node.js, a Gazelle-inspired file base system with full-text search, hashtags, and temporary HTTP(S) download links served by a built-in web server, native support for FidoNet-style message networks (FTN) with BinkleyTerm-style outbound (BSO) import/export and a built-in BinkP mailer for inbound and outbound message routing, built-in support for BBS door-gaming services like BBSLink, DoorParty, Exodus, and CombatNet, and a gamified achievement system. User accounts and message/file data are stored in SQLite, and passwords are protected with PBKDF2-based encryption. ENiGMA½ can be installed via an automated shell install script, manually from source, or via an official Docker image, making setup accessible to both newcomers and experienced sysadmins. As with the entire genre, there is no company behind ENiGMA½ and no pricing whatsoever; it is a fully free, community-driven open-source project, maintained primarily by NuSkooler with contributions from the retrocomputing and BBS hobbyist community, and showcased on live, publicly reachable installations such as the project's own Xibalba headquarters board. Its target users are retrocomputing hobbyists, BBS revivalists, and developers nostalgic for or curious about pre-web online culture, who want to either run their own modern BBS or connect to others in the small but persistent worldwide BBS scene. Within that niche, its main competitors and points of comparison are other modern or legacy BBS software packages such as Mystic BBS, Synchronet, and WWIV, against which ENiGMA½ differentiates itself through its Node.js-based cross-platform architecture, extensive JavaScript moddability, and unusually deep native door-game emulation support.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = 'fcc4c746-3637-450b-9b93-e0c4703382b5';

